    11→
    12→# Scheduling Problem Classifications
    13→
    14→Fleet maintenance scheduling draws from several well-studied optimization problem classes. Understanding these classifications helps in selecting appropriate solution methods and leveraging existing algorithms.
    15→
    16→## Resource-Constrained Project Scheduling Problem (RCPSP)
    17→
    18→RCPSP is the most directly applicable model for maintenance scheduling. It involves scheduling activities with durations and resource requirements while respecting precedence constraints.
    19→
    20→### Standard RCPSP Definition
    21→
    22→**Given**:
    23→
    24→- Set of activities J = {1, 2, ..., n}
    25→- Duration pⱼ for each activity j
    26→- Renewable resources R with capacity Cᵣ per period
    27→- Resource requirement rⱼᵣ for activity j on resource r
    28→- Precedence relations (i, j) meaning i must finish before j starts
    29→
    30→**Find**: Start time Sⱼ for each activity
    31→
    32→**Minimize**: Project makespan (max{Sⱼ + pⱼ})
    33→
    34→```typescript
    35→interface RCPSPProblem {
    36→  activities: {
    37→    id: string;
    38→    duration: number;
    39→    resourceRequirements: Map<string, number>;
    40→    predecessors: string[];
    41→  }[];
    42→
    43→  resources: {
    44→    id: string;
    45→    capacity: number;
    46→    renewable: boolean;
    47→  }[];
    48→
    49→  objective: 'minimize_makespan';
    50→}
    51→```
    52→
    53→### RCPSP Variants for Maintenance
    54→
    55→**Multi-Mode RCPSP (MRCPSP)**
    56→
    57→Each activity can be executed in different modes with different durations and resource requirements. In maintenance context: different crew sizes or equipment options.
    58→
    59→```typescript
    60→interface MultiModeActivity {
    61→  id: string;
    62→  modes: {
    63→    modeId: string;
    64→    duration: number;
    65→    resourceRequirements: Map<string, number>;
    66→    cost: number;
    67→  }[];
    68→}
    69→```
    70→
    71→**RCPSP with Time Windows**
    72→
    73→Activities must start within a time window. Directly maps to maintenance tolerance windows.
    74→
    75→```typescript
    76→interface TimeWindowActivity {
    77→  id: string;
    78→  duration: number;
    79→  earliestStart: number;
    80→  latestStart: number;  // Or latestFinish
    81→  resourceRequirements: Map<string, number>;
    82→}
    83→```
    84→
    85→**Resource-Constrained Project Scheduling with Discounted Cash Flows (RCPSP-DC)**
    86→
    87→Considers time value of money. Relevant for long-horizon maintenance planning.
    88→
    89→### Applying RCPSP to Maintenance
    90→
    91→A maintenance schedule maps to RCPSP:
    92→
    93→- **Activities**: Maintenance events
    94→- **Durations**: Event duration in periods
    95→- **Resources**: Technician hours, maintenance bays
    96→- **Precedence**: Component dependencies, logical sequences
    97→- **Time windows**: Mileage-based maintenance windows
    98→
    99→```typescript
   100→function maintenanceToRCPSP(
   101→  fleet: Asset[],
   102→  maintenanceTypes: MaintenanceType[],
   103→  horizon: number
   104→): RCPSPProblem {
   105→  const activities = fleet.flatMap(asset =>
   106→    maintenanceTypes.map(type => ({
   107→      id: `${asset.id}_${type.id}`,
   108→      duration: type.durationPeriods,
   109→      resourceRequirements: new Map([
   110→        ['technician_hours', type.manHours],
   111→        ['bay', type.requiresBay ? 1 : 0]
   112→      ]),
   113→      predecessors: type.prerequisites.map(p => `${asset.id}_${p}`),
   114→      earliestStart: calculateEarliestPeriod(asset, type),
   115→      latestStart: calculateLatestPeriod(asset, type)
   116→    }))
   117→  );
   118→
   119→  return { activities, resources, objective: 'minimize_makespan' };
   120→}
   121→```
   122→
   123→## Job-Shop Scheduling Problem (JSSP)
   124→
   125→JSSP models jobs that must visit multiple machines in a specific order. Less common in maintenance but applicable for multi-stage overhauls.
   126→
   127→### JSSP Definition
   128→
   129→**Given**:
   130→
   131→- Set of jobs J = {1, ..., n}
   132→- Set of machines M = {1, ..., m}
   133→- Each job j has operations Oⱼ = (oⱼ₁, ..., oⱼₘ) to be processed in order
   134→- Processing time pⱼₖ for operation k of job j
   135→
   136→**Constraints**:
   137→
   138→- Operations within a job must be processed in order
   139→- Each machine processes one operation at a time
   140→
   141→**Minimize**: Makespan
   142→
   143→### JSSP in Maintenance Context
   144→
   145→Multi-stage overhauls where an asset moves through stations:
   146→
   147→1. Inspection bay
   148→2. Mechanical workshop
   149→3. Electrical workshop
   150→4. Paint shop
   151→5. Testing bay
   152→
   153→```typescript
   154→interface OverhaulJob {
   155→  assetId: string;
   156→  operations: {
   157→    station: string;
   158→    duration: number;
   159→    sequence: number;
   160→  }[];
   161→}
   162→
   163→interface JSPProblem {
   164→  jobs: OverhaulJob[];
   165→  machines: {
   166→    id: string;
   167→    capacity: number;  // Usually 1 for classic JSSP
   168→  }[];
   169→}
   170→```
   171→
   172→### Flexible Job-Shop (FJSSP)
   173→
   174→Each operation can be processed on one of several machines. Maps to maintenance where events can be done at different facilities.
   175→
   176→```typescript
   177→interface FlexibleOperation {
   178→  id: string;
   179→  eligibleMachines: {
   180→    machineId: string;
   181→    processingTime: number;
   182→  }[];
   183→}
   184→```
   185→
   186→## Vehicle Routing Problem (VRP)
   187→
   188→VRP involves routing vehicles to serve locations. Applicable when maintenance occurs at distributed locations or assets must travel to central facilities.
   189→
   190→### Classic VRP Definition
   191→
   192→**Given**:
   193→
   194→- Depot location
   195→- Set of customers with demands
   196→- Fleet of vehicles with capacity
   197→- Travel times/distances between locations
   198→
   199→**Find**: Routes for vehicles starting and ending at depot
   200→
   201→**Minimize**: Total travel distance or time
   202→
   203→### VRP Variants for Maintenance
   204→
   205→**VRP with Time Windows (VRPTW)**
   206→
   207→Customers must be visited within time windows. Maps to scheduled maintenance visits.
   208→
   209→```typescript
   210→interface VRPTWCustomer {
   211→  id: string;
   212→  location: Coordinates;
   213→  serviceTime: number;
   214→  demand: number;
   215→  timeWindow: { earliest: number; latest: number };
   216→}
   217→
   218→interface VRPTWProblem {
   219→  depot: Coordinates;
   220→  customers: VRPTWCustomer[];
   221→  vehicles: {
   222→    id: string;
   223→    capacity: number;
   224→    maxDuration: number;
   225→  }[];
   226→}
   227→```
   228→
   229→**Periodic VRP (PVRP)**
   230→
   231→Customers require visits with certain frequencies over a planning period. Directly applicable to distributed maintenance.
   232→
   233→```typescript
   234→interface PeriodicCustomer {
   235→  id: string;
   236→  location: Coordinates;
   237→  visitFrequency: number;  // Visits per planning period
   238→  allowedDays: number[];   // Which days visits can occur
   239→}
   240→```
   241→
   242→### Maintenance Applications of VRP
   243→
   244→**Mobile maintenance crews**: Routing technicians to asset locations
   245→
   246→```typescript
   247→interface MobileMaintenanceVRP {
   248→  maintenanceTasks: {
   249→    assetLocation: Coordinates;
   250→    taskDuration: number;
   251→    dueWindow: { earliest: Date; latest: Date };
   252→    skillsRequired: string[];
   253→  }[];
   254→
   255→  crews: {
   256→    startLocation: Coordinates;
   257→    skills: string[];
   258→    maxWorkHours: number;
   259→  }[];
   260→}
   261→```
   262→
   263→**Asset transport to depot**: Moving assets for centralized maintenance
   264→
   265→```typescript
   266→interface AssetTransportProblem {
   267→  assets: {
   268→    currentLocation: Coordinates;
   269→    maintenanceDue: Date;
   270→    transportCost: number;
   271→  }[];
   272→
   273→  depot: {
   274→    location: Coordinates;
   275→    capacity: number;
   276→    queueTime: number;
   277→  };
   278→}
   279→```
   280→
   281→## Bin Packing and Knapsack Problems
   282→
   283→These combinatorial problems appear as subproblems in maintenance scheduling.
   284→
   285→### Bin Packing
   286→
   287→Pack items into bins of fixed capacity minimizing bins used. In maintenance: pack events into periods minimizing overtime.
   288→
   289→```typescript
   290→interface BinPackingSubproblem {
   291→  events: {
   292→    id: string;
   293→    manHours: number;
   294→  }[];
   295→
   296→  periodCapacity: number;
   297→
   298→  // Output: which events in which period
   299→  assignment: Map<string, number>;  // eventId -> periodIndex
   300→}
   301→```
   302→
   303→### Knapsack
   304→
   305→Select items to maximize value within capacity. In maintenance: select which maintenance to perform within budget or capacity.
   306→
   307→```typescript
   308→interface KnapsackSubproblem {
   309→  events: {
   310→    id: string;
   311→    value: number;    // Priority or risk reduction
   312→    cost: number;     // Man-hours or cost
   313→  }[];
   314→
   315→  capacity: number;   // Available resources
   316→
   317→  // Output: which events to include
   318→  selected: string[];
   319→}
   320→```
   321→
   322→## Multi-Period and Rolling Horizon
   323→
   324→Real maintenance scheduling extends over time with rolling updates.
   325→
   326→### Multi-Period Scheduling
   327→
   328→Decisions in one period affect options in later periods.
   329→
   330→```typescript
   331→interface MultiPeriodSchedule {
   332→  periods: {
   333→    periodId: number;
   334→    events: ScheduledEvent[];
   335→    resourceUsage: Map<string, number>;
   336→  }[];
   337→
   338→  carryover: {
   339→    unscheduledEvents: string[];
   340→    resourceBalance: Map<string, number>;
   341→    maintenanceDebts: Map<string, number>;
   342→  };
   343→}
   344→```
   345→
   346→### Rolling Horizon Decomposition
   347→
   348→Solve a window, fix near-term decisions, roll forward.
   349→
   350→```typescript
   351→interface RollingHorizonConfig {
   352→  totalHorizon: number;      // Total planning period
   353→  windowSize: number;        // Periods solved at once
   354→  fixedHorizon: number;      // Periods locked after each solve
   355→  overlapPeriods: number;    // Stability buffer
   356→
   357→  // Different detail levels
   358→  detailedPeriods: number;   // Full detail
   359→  aggregatePeriods: number;  // Reduced detail
   360→}
   361→
   362→function solveRollingHorizon(
   363→  config: RollingHorizonConfig,
   364→  problem: SchedulingProblem
   365→): Schedule {
   366→  let currentPeriod = 0;
   367→  let schedule: Schedule = createEmptySchedule();
   368→
   369→  while (currentPeriod < config.totalHorizon) {
   370→    // Extract window
   371→    const windowProblem = extractWindow(
   372→      problem,
   373→      currentPeriod,
   374→      config.windowSize
   375→    );
   376→
   377→    // Solve window
   378→    const windowSolution = solveWindow(windowProblem, schedule);
   379→
   380→    // Fix decisions in fixed horizon
   381→    schedule = fixDecisions(
   382→      schedule,
   383→      windowSolution,
   384→      currentPeriod,
   385→      config.fixedHorizon
   386→    );
   387→
   388→    // Roll forward
   389→    currentPeriod += config.fixedHorizon;
   390→  }
   391→
   392→  return schedule;
   393→}
   394→```
   395→
   396→## Problem Complexity Summary
   397→
   398→Understanding complexity helps set expectations:
   399→
   400→- **LP**: Polynomial time (P)
   401→- **RCPSP**: NP-hard (general case)
   402→- **JSSP**: NP-hard (strongly)
   403→- **VRP**: NP-hard
   404→- **Bin Packing**: NP-hard (but good approximations exist)
   405→
   406→```typescript
   407→interface ProblemSizeGuidelines {
   408→  rcpsp: {
   409→    easyInstances: 'up to 60 activities';
   410→    mediumInstances: '60-120 activities';
   411→    hardInstances: '120+ activities need decomposition';
   412→  };
   413→
   414→  jssp: {
   415→    classicBenchmarks: '10 jobs x 10 machines';
   416→    industrialScale: '100+ jobs needs metaheuristics';
   417→  };
   418→
   419→  vrp: {
   420→    exactMethods: 'up to 50-100 customers';
   421→    heuristics: '1000+ customers';
   422→  };
   423→}
   424→```
   425→
   426→## Mapping Maintenance Problems
   427→
   428→### Single-Depot Maintenance
   429→
   430→Assets maintained at central facility:
   431→
   432→```
   433→RCPSP + Bin Packing
   434→- Activities = maintenance events
   435→- Resources = bays, technicians
   436→- Bins = time periods
   437→```
   438→
   439→### Multi-Depot Maintenance
   440→
   441→Assets maintained at multiple facilities:
   442→
   443→```
   444→RCPSP + Assignment + VRP
   445→- Assign assets to facilities (assignment)
   446→- Route assets to facilities (VRP)
   447→- Schedule within facilities (RCPSP)
   448→```
   449→
   450→### Mobile Maintenance
   451→
   452→Technicians travel to asset locations:
   453→
   454→```
   455→VRPTW + RCPSP
   456→- Route technicians (VRPTW)
   457→- Schedule at each location (RCPSP)
   458→```
   459→
